My last @superrare.co drop of 2022 is LIVE with a low reserve of 0.069 eth. Winning bid will also receive a 1/1 airdrop from my sold out @sloika.xyz collection and all bidders will receive a special edition piece. My all time favorite photo from Manhattan Beach pier with the festive holiday lights and an insane sunset to boot. Not often do you get a lingering sunset to stay around until the pier lights come on so this was definitely one of those moments where everything aligned perfectly. Used a slow shutter speed to capture the movement of the wave, adding nice texture to the foreground. A perfect photo bundle for the holiday season.

My final @withfoundation drop for 2022 is live. The ultimate photo of Christmas in Los Angeles with prominent holiday colors and a dusting of snow after a fresh winter storm. The skyline is lit with green LED lights; most notably the Wilshire Grand and City Hall. A holiday light show displaying Christmas ornaments is showcased on Los Angeles’ tallest highrise. The red comes from the colors reflecting off the buildings as the sun sets in the opposite direction. I aligned the city directly under Strawberry Peak; which takes on the shape of a Santa hat. One of the rarest photos of Los Angeles, and the perfect release for the holiday season.

Snowmageddon Los Angeles 2023. Last significant storms that brought snow down to lower elevations were in 2019 and 2020. Levels this year are the lowest I’ve seen in my many years capturing this city I call home. My goal in documenting my city is to continuously find unique angles paired with historic conditions. The juxtaposition of city vs nature is undeniable in this composition. An epic morning of light and layers.

The blizzard that keeps on giving. Never has there been so much snow on these lower peaks. This compressed telephoto shot lines up Sofi stadium, the Hollywood sign and layers of iced out San Gabriel Mountains. These are the conditions that make me love photographing my city. Stormageddon 2023 is one for the books.

YOSEMITE MOONLIT FIREFALL 2023 
 
A unicorn trip up in Yosemite these past few days. The atmospheric river and flood closure were presenting obstacles from achieving this photo but once the park announced a full reopening on 5/1, I drove up through the night hoping for a break in the clouds. I arrived at Tunnel View around 1:30am and was greeted with some epic low fog. The moon peaked out from the thick clouds here and there so after about an hour of timelapsing, I made my way down to El Cap picnic area only to be greeted by the thick fog I was just above. I setup in the hopes that I would catch a break in the clouds and sure enough the moon popped out around a bit after 3am providing enough light on the falls and lingering fog to pull this off. Shortly after, El Cap moved back behind a thick veil of fog all the way through moonset. I packed up and made my way back to Tunnel View for sunrise to capture probably my most favorite low fog sunrise shot to date. Working on the edit now for my next 1/1 on SR. A night running on fumes, but well worth it.

My new 1/1 ‘Ascension’ is live on @superrare.co and captures the most beautiful cloud inversion I’ve had the pleasure to witness. As the sun broke free from the clouds, it radiated warm light onto the low fog hovering over the valley floor like golden waves. El Capitan emerged from behind its veil and Bridalveil Fall dumped a heavy pour into the mist. Evergreen treetops poked out through the fog as ebbed and flowed in a hypnotic trance. A moment of peaceful serenity humbled by the beauty of Mother Nature.

Perseids 2023. Spent the night in the Mojave area stargazing until the pre-dawn hours. The new moon definitely helped with the overall darkness. Not the best year in terms of frequency but a great year to shoot towards the anti-radiant catching some nice fireballs. Saw some of the biggest I’ve ever seen this year, as always a lot pointed in a different direction. This is a stack from a 3-hour timelapse blending the brightest. Working on my other edit from my second camera pointed towards the radiant. Foreground shot at twilight and blended with the final sky stack.

24 hours in Yosemite hosted by  @yosemiteviewlodge which is where I stay every time I visit. Arrived at a cloudy Tunnel View after midnight and greeted by low fog down in the valley. Was able to capture cartrails driving through along with the full moon blasting light on El Cap and Bridalveil. Made my way down to the valley to capture a moonlit Firefall around 3am which is the rarest phenomenon in Yosemite that I’ve been able to capture on camera. Headed back up to Tunnel View to capture one of the most spectacular sunrises I’ve been fortunate enough to witness. Needless to say, hands down the best conditions I’ve seen within a single day.

My first @exchange.art SOL series featuring my wide field astrophotography is live.  I’ve always had an interest in the night sky. As a kid going camping and looking up at the stars it was always the mystery of the unknown. From a photography standpoint, the technical difficulty of a successful wide field astrophotography shot is unmatched. Not only shooting in the dark, but also high ISO noise management, different exposures , stacking/tracking and all the post processing that comes with it. I’m very passionate about landscape photography which is why wide field astrophotography showcasing both the land and Milky Way elements was the perfect combination.
